{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Power and Effects in Practice",
    "objective": "Synthesize power calculations for parallel branches with the identification of thermal and chemical effects in a real-world DC system.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "In a practical installation, you will often see different electrical effects occurring simultaneously on the same supply. Whether a component is designed to produce heat (thermal) or facilitate a chemical change (chemical), the total load on the power source is always the sum of the individual power demands.",
      "To analyze a system, you must select the correct power formula based on the known values ($P=VI$, $P=I^2R$, or $P=V^2/R$) for each branch and then combine them to determine the total circuit power ($P_t$)."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are inspecting a 24V DC backup system. The circuit consists of two parallel branches: \n1. Branch A contains a 12Ω heating element used for moisture control. \n2. Branch B is a secondary battery cell being charged at a constant current of 1.5A. \n\nCalculate the total power ($P_t$) consumed by this circuit and identify which specific electrical effect (thermal or chemical) is occurring in each branch, explaining the physical reason for your choice.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Total Power (Pt) = 84W. Calculation: Branch A ($V^2/R$) is $24^2 / 12 = 48W$. Branch B ($V \\times I$) is $24 \\times 1.5 = 36W$. $48W + 36W = 84W$.",
      "Branch A Effect: Thermal effect. Reason: Current passing through the 12Ω resistance causes atomic vibration, generating heat.",
      "Branch B Effect: Chemical effect. Reason: Current passing through the liquid electrolyte of the battery causes a chemical change (charging)."
    ],
    "hint": "Calculate the power for each branch independently using the 24V supply. Remember that Branch A uses resistance while Branch B uses current. For the effects, think about the medium the current is passing through (solid conductor vs. liquid electrolyte)."
  }
}

